<center><table border=0><tr><td><center><H2><font face=arial>Exactly My Point</font></H2></center>
<font face=arial size=2><b>Posted By:</b> <A HREF="/cgi-local/whois2.cgi?The RealmWeaver">The RealmWeaver</a><br>
<b>Posted On:</b> 10:10 a.m. 6/5/1999<br>
<b>Subject:</b> Exactly My Point<p>
<br><center><img src="http://www.everworld.net/pvpquest/images/divider.gif" width=452 height=22 border=0></center><BR><P ALIGN=CENTER><b>In Reply To:</b> <A HREF="http://www.everworld.net/cgi-local/pvp.cgi?read=2022" TARGET=_self>Verant supports the PvP server</A> (TheBlack)
</STRONG><FONT SIZE=2 color=#FFFFFF FACE=arial>
<P>> Good point. That was just one of the problems that the PvP

<BR>&gt; server faced over the past couple months that Brad/Verant has
<BR>&gt; solved for us. Currently they are working on fixing the DOT
<BR>&gt; issue. Brad McQuaid wants this server to be successful, and they
<BR>&gt; are willing to put the time in (within reason) to help assure
<BR>&gt; this.
<P>The most important thing in this paragraph is your qualifier - "within reason." For Verant, "within reason" means they delegate work according to which portion of the playing population will respond favorably to which changes. While I'm sure Brad McQuaid supports the PVP server and wants to to succeed, he, like all other game creators, is a slave of sorts to profit; and right now, profits from EverQuest come primarily from non-PVP players with non-PVP problems to be solved.
<P>&gt; As for the pure fighters, I don't know if anything can be done
<BR>&gt; to make them competitive 1 on 1 with the rest of the classes.
<BR>&gt; Access to limited SoTW abilities, better bows, and flurry
<BR>&gt; attacks are a few possible ideas to help fighters. They are
<BR>&gt; however design enhancements, not fixes for glaring shortcomings
<BR>&gt; or bugs.
<P>Unfortunately, this is not just the case with fighters. The major problems exist not in subtle class differences, but in the fact that EverQuest simply was NOT designed to be a PVP game. Against monsters, the classes are all fairly balanced, but when it comes to PVP combat, all but 3 or 4 of the classes become relatively obsolete. The changes necessary to make PVP viable and workable in EQ are simply too large to ever come about. Even if all the bugs and subtle problems are fixed with PVP, the glaring flaws and imbalances will still exist, because there is simply NO WAY to balance those flaws without in turn imbalancing non-PVP players, and my prediction is, no matter how many people get bored and go +PVP, the non-PVP will ALWAYS outnumber PVP by, at the very, very, least, 4 to 1.
<P>[The RealmWeaver]
<P>
</FONT></td></tr></table></P>
